  _leadParagraph: The Wenmar son is the teenage member of the family seated nearest
    the cold hearth during Voss's tax demand.
  _backgroundParagraph: 'He belongs to the same two authored states as his parents:
    the tense inn bench before payment and the occupied cottage after the household
    is secured.'
  _perspectiveParagraph: 'His visual direction is deliberately quiet: a guarded posture
    and eyes lowered to boots he studies as if they, too, might be taken.'
